data.text: When quite is used with an adjective before a noun, it comes before
quite同形容词连用修饰名词时，置于a或an之前，可以说It's quite a small house或Their house is quite small，但不说It's a quite small house。

data.chText: 非常鲜美 / 惊人 / 空 / 出众
这是个截然不同的问题。
data.enText: This is quite a different problem.

data.chText: 我非常高兴在此等候您。
data.enText: I'm quite happy to wait for you here.

data.enText: Flying is quite the best way to travel.

data.chText: 这事不完全像我想的那么简单。
data.enText: It wasn't quite as simple as I thought it would be.

data.enText: I've had quite enough of your tantrums.

data.chText: 我不太清楚下一步该怎么办。
data.enText: I don't quite know what to do next.

data.enText: Quite apart from all the work, he had financial problems.
The theatre was not quite (= was almost) full.

data.chText: 那好像是在阿尔卑斯山，但又不尽然。
data.enText: It's like being in the Alps, but not quite.

data.chText: “我简直认为她喜爱动物胜过喜爱人。”“没错儿。”比尔说道。
data.enText: ‘I almost think she prefers animals to people.’ ‘ Quite right too ,’ said Bill.

data.chText: “对不起我太为难你了。”“没关系。”
data.enText: ‘I'm sorry to be so difficult.’ ‘ That's quite all right .’
to a great degree; very; really

data.chText: 我能清清楚楚地看见它。
data.enText: I can see it quite clearly.

data.enText: ‘You've no intention of coming back?’ ‘I'm quite sorry, but no, I have not.’
used to agree with sb or show that you understand them

data.chText: “那次事故之后，他一定是像惊弓之鸟。”“可不是。”
data.enText: ‘He's bound to feel shaken after his accident.’ ‘Quite.’
used to show that a person or thing is particularly impressive or unusual in some way

data.chText: 我们搬到伦敦后，感觉生活变化很大。
data.enText: We found it quite a change when we moved to London.

a large number or amount of sth

data.chText: quite比fairly词义稍强，而rather又比quite词义稍强。在北美英语中，rather不很通用。pretty与上述词含义相同，也用于非正式英国英语：
data.enText: Quite is a little stronger than fairly and rather is a little stronger than quite . Rather is not very common in NAmE ; pretty has the same meaning and this is used in informal BrE too.

data.chText: 在英国英语中，quite含义有二：
data.enText: In BrE quite has two meanings.

data.chText: 今天我感到相当累。与表示极端状态的形容词（即非级差形容词）连用，意为完全地、绝对地：
data.enText: (= fairly tired ). With adjectives that describe an extreme state (‘non-gradable’ adjectives) it means ‘completely’ or ‘absolutely’.

data.chText: 与某些形容词连用，两种含义均有可能，究竟属于哪一种由说话者的重音和语调决定：
data.enText: With some adjectives, both meanings are possible. The speaker’s stress and intonation will show you which is meant.

data.chText: 你的文章还不错（相当好，不过还可以更好）。
你的文章简直太好了（非常好，尤指没预料到）。
data.enText: (= very good, especially when this is unexpected ).

data.chText: 在北美英语中，quite通常含very之意，而非fairly或rather。表示后一种意思用pretty。
data.enText: In NAmE quite usually means something like ‘very’, not ‘fairly’ or ‘rather’. Pretty is used instead for this sense.

ex.chText: 她相当喜欢他，但还没到嫁给他的程度。
ex.enText: She quite likes him, but not enough to marry him.

ex.chText: 现在她很喜欢自己的新工作。
ex.enText: Now she quite enjoys her new job.

item.bx: 可直接修饰 like, enjoy, agree 之类动词和某些过去分词（位置在其之前），而 very 不可以。

ex.enText: The food here is quite good.
She's doing quite well at college.

item.bx: 在英国英语中，修饰形容词或副词时为减弱语，即减弱所修饰词的程度，语气弱于 very，一般译为“比较”、“还算”，但在美国英语中则为加强语，等于 very。

ex.chText: 我们的假期过得很愉快。
ex.enText: We had quite an enjoyable holiday.

ex.chText: 理查德是个相当不错的球员。
ex.enText: Richard is quite a good player.

item.bx: 用来修饰作定语的形容词时，通常置于不定冠词之前：

ex.chText: 她相当喜欢他，但还没到嫁给他的程度。

ex.enText: Now she quite enjoys her new job.

ex.chText: 他的狗丢了后，他非常难受。
ex.enText: He was very unhappy when he lost his dog.

item.bx: 修饰形容词或副词时为加强语（可与美国英语中的 quite 换用）。

ex.chText: 他们非常喜欢西班牙语。

item.bx: 修饰 like, enjoy 之类动词时要用 very much，但位置应在动词的宾语之后。

tr: to a degree (not used with a negative)
of an unusually noticeable or exceptional or remarkable kind (not used with a negative)
actually or truly or to an extreme
example: it's quite the thing to do

value.def: You use quite to indicate that something is the case to a fairly great extent. Quite is less emphatic than 'very' and 'extremely'.

example.ex: I felt quite bitter about it at the time...
example.tran: 当时我对这件事感到相当怨愤。

example.ex: I was doing quite well, but I wasn't earning a lot of money...
example.tran: 我干得还算不错，可是挣的钱却不算多。

example.ex: Well, actually it requires quite a bit of work and research...
example.tran: 嗯，实际上这需要花不少的工夫，做点研究。

example.ex: I was quite a long way away, on the terrace...
example.tran: 我在露台上，离得还挺远。

gramarinfo.label: ADV adj/adv, ADV <l>a</l> n, ADV before v

value.def: You use quite to emphasize what you are saying.

example.ex: It is quite clear that we were firing in self defence...
example.tran: 事实很清楚，我们开枪是出于自卫。

example.ex: That's a general British failing. In the USA it's quite different...
example.tran: 那是英国人的普遍缺点。在美国，情况就大不一样了。

example.ex: I can state quite definitely it will be terrible...
example.tran: 我可以非常明确地说，情况会十分糟糕。

example.ex: This was a serious breach of trust quite apart from the gravity of any offence...
example.tran: 这不光是情节重大的犯罪行为，还是一种严重的背信行为。

example.ex: I quite agree with you. That's a good way of looking at it.
example.tran: 我很赞同你的观点，这是看待该问题的一个很好的角度。

value.def: You use quite after a negative to make what you are saying weaker or less definite.

example.ex: Something here is not quite right...
example.tran: 这里有什么地方不太对劲。

example.ex: After treatment he was able to continue but he was never quite the same...
example.tran: 治疗之后他又可以继续下去了，可是再也恢复不到从前的状态了。

example.ex: We still can't quite believe he's here with us after all this time...
example.tran: 我们还是不太敢相信，过了这么久，他居然还和我们一起呆在这里。

example.ex: And at the beginning, I didn't quite understand what all this was about...
example.tran: 我起初不太明白这一切究竟是怎么回事。

example.ex: That wasn't quite what I meant.

gramarinfo.label: with brd-neg, ADV group, ADV before v

value.tran: (与否定词连用，表示语气较弱或不确定)

value.def: You use quite in front of a noun group to emphasize that a person or thing is very impressive or unusual.

example.ex: 'Oh, he's quite a character,' Sean replied...
example.tran: “喔，他真是个了不起的人，”肖恩回答说。
波士顿，真是一座伟大的城市。

value.tran: （用于名词词组前，表示强调）出众的，了不起的，不同寻常的

value.def: You can say 'quite' to express your agreement with someone.

example.ex: 'And if you buy the record it's your choice isn't it.' — 'Quite'...
example.tran: “如果你买这张唱片，那是你的选择，不是吗？”——“可不是嘛。”

example.ex: 'I won't say over the air who it is.' — 'No, quite.'
example.tran: “我不会在电话里说出那个人是谁。”——“对，的确应该这样。”

value.boxu_tran: quite 可以用于 a 或 an 后接形容词加名词的结构之前。例如，可以说 It's quite an old car (这是一辆很旧的车)，也可以说 The car is quite old (这辆车很旧了)；可以说 It was quite a warm day (那是相当暖和的一天)，也可以说 The day was quite warm (那天很暖和)。需要注意的是，在此类句子中，quite 置于不定冠词的前面，例如不可以说It's a quite old car。quite 可以修饰形容词和副词，其程度稍强于 fairly，但弱于 very。quite 可以表示某事物比预料中更加具备某特点，例如，Nobody here's ever heard of it but it is actually quite common (这里没有人听说过它，但是它实际上颇为常见)。注意不要混淆 quite 与 quiet。
value.boxu_usage: You can use quite in front of a or an when it is followed by an adjective plus noun. For example, you can say 'It's quite an old car' as well as 'The car is quite old', and 'It was quite a warm day' as well as 'The day was quite warm'. Note that, in sentences like these, quite comes in front of the indefinite article. You cannot say, for example, 'It's a quite old car'. Quite can be used to modify adjectives and adverbs, and is slightly stronger than fairly but less strong than very. Quite may suggest that something has more of a quality than expected. Nobody here's ever heard of it but it is actually quite common. Take care not to confuse quite and quiet.
